rmk: This bird was found by Thibaut  Chansac on 8 June 2019, he heard and recorded it booming.  Neil Baker and I went to look for it the next day and heard and recorded what we presumed to be the same bird booming.  It was counter-singing with a second bird about several hundred meters away.  This is the first record of this species in Tanzania since it was reported from the Rukwa Valley by International Red Locust Control biologists (Vesey-Fitzgerald, D. & Beesley, J. 1960. An Annotated List of the Birds of the Rukwa Valley.  Tanganyika notes and Records. 54:91–110) in the 1950's.  The birds were not seen, only heard.  They were in a seasonally flooded wetland dominated by grasses about 100 cm tall in about 40 cm of standing water.
